      <hedline>
        <hl1>Diversity and G.E.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Indiana University Kelly School of Buisness Dean Dan R Dalton letter on September 3 article holds that while G E may meet diversity goals for high-ranking officers, it promotes progam that offers opportunities for new generation of university faculty members (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While G.E. may not have met diversity goals for high-ranking officers, it is behind a program that  delivers incredible opportunities for a new generation of prospective university faculty members.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While G.E. may not have met diversity goals for high-ranking officers, it is behind a program that  delivers incredible opportunities for a new generation of prospective university faculty members.</p>
        <p>This program is Faculty for the Future, founded in 1990 and fully financed by the G.E. Fund. Its objective is to increase the number of underrepresented minorities who take faculty positions in business, engineering and science schools. While there are other elements to the program, it provides generous scholarships for minority doctoral students.</p>
        <p>Over 800 have benefited so far.</p>
        <p>DAN R. DALTON  Bloomington, Ind., Sept. 8</p>
        <p>The writer is dean of the Kelley School of Business at Indiana University.</p>
      </block>
